description.text:

I also like to include some latest improvement from evanevery(http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13261) such as stress relief and other holes for additional fan mount.
However, evanevery's design is made for 5.5mm~5.9mm thickness board which won't work for standard 5mm board. So, This drawing is designing for board thickness tolerance in 4.6mm~5.2mm. All t-slot also have stress relief to prevent cracking under stress.
I try to pack all small parts into the window to save the board usage.
Use this drawing and cut with laser. Make sure the board thickness is in the range of 4.6mm~5.2mm.

description.text:
PURPOSE
These mounting stands allow the attachment of the printrbot simple metal to a surface to restrict unnecessary movement.

PARTS
There are three parts that make up the mounting stand assembly:

  1. Back End Mounting Stand
  2. Front Left Mounting Stand
  3. Front Right Mounting Stand

Each of these parts are designed to slide onto the printrbot simple metal's bottom frame snugly (about 0.4mm of leeway in the grooves). Note that the left and right notation is with respect of the user facing the front end of the printrbot, though the parts will only fit on their respective positions so the assembly is self explanatory.

I am working on providing real photos of the mounting stands on my printrbot and supplying dimensional schematics on each part. If there are any improvements, problems, or concerns, please leave a comment. Thank you.

UPDATE LOG
4/27/2016 Better photo renderings of each part added
Fixed orientation on assembly rendering
Renamed STL Files for consistancy
4/25/2016 STL models added

Printrbot

Simple Black

Attachment Directions

  1. Check to see if there are any defects in the parts.
    a. Make sure grooves are clear of any extra or dragged filament.
    b. Make sure grooves are straight.

  2. Affix the respective parts to the printrbot
    a. Line up the grooves of the part with the frame and slide the part onto the frame.
    (Note that it may take some force to install the part)

  3. Position the printrbot in the desired location on the surface.

  4. Use screws to fixate the mounting stands to the surface via the 4mm diameter mounting holes. (Adjust as necessary depending on your situation. I did not design the mounting holes with any specific hardware in mind.)

description.text:
Sturdy and simple frame brace.
Y-axis belt roll holder with room for a nut and washer ( print them with 100% fill).
Drill 8mm holes in the middle of front, aft and center frame 20mm from the underside (the middle hole can be 10mm to give some extra play).
put a 40 cm 8mm thread bar through and 8mm nuts on both sides on all frame parts.
this setup take up the force from the belt just on the right spot and do not transfere the tension force to any other part of the construction.
The roll holder attachment screws need to be countersunked 3mm, with a 5mm drill, so they are flush with the surface, otherways they interfere with the front nut
You dont need to tear down the printer to install it, just put it on the side and drill the holes, it is a 5 min job, oh well...10 min then... !
Needed:
1 pcs 40cm 8mm threadbar
6 pcs 8mm washers (not nessesery)
6 pcs 8mm nuts

description.text:
Well, a classmate told me about designing this emblem, After having a look at it, I decided to accept the challenge, without even looking if it already was uploaded (it was). And well, after a couple of hours I got this result. I hope you like it.

I leave the image i took as reference, and a photo of my printed emblem (the quality is not the best, as I'm having some problems with the printer)

Bueno, la semana pasada, un compañero de clase me dijo a ver si sería capaz de diseñarlo. Despues de echarle un vistazo, decidí aceptar el "reto", sin ni siquiera mirar si ya estaba publicado (que lo estaba). Tras un par de horas diseñándolo, tuve este resultado.

Dejo la imagen que tomé de referencia, y una foto de mi impresión (aunque la calidad no es la misma, ya que estoy teniendo algún problema con la impresora)
As all my designs, I used CATIA v5 to design it

description.text:
Here is a set of addons for DJI FlameWheel F550. It consist of following parts:

  • 3rd floor board to mount flight controller above battery. GPS/Magnetometer and companion computer may be attached there also.
  • Bottom mount to attach Tarot FY680 landing gears. Because overall size of mount is too large for my 3D printer I split it on two parts they are different a bit due to asymmetrical cutouts of F550 bottom board.
  • Bottom mount back part is to isolate some modules from bottom board (which is power distribution board) and to fasten bottom mount parts with plastic zip ties and bolts.

Some moment I decided I need more space between F550 bottom board and ground. So I needed to attach landing gears from my FY680. As result I implemented bottom mount for FY680 landing gears. Next time I realised I need more room for flight controller and companion computer so I implemented 3rd floor board.

this is a solid fix mount usable on anything from a multirotor, a land based rc or even body/bike/dash mounting.

suited for both the turnigy 1040p action cam, Sj4000 range and the multitude of Chinese clones knocking about.

lightweight with no movable parts and simple camera retention method.

included STL's are a horizontal version and a 22° version for fast forward tilt.

Black versions are PLA, Silver is ABS, both printed well, both nice and solid, both take a kickin well (Ive "cough cough" tested their durability extensively..........which reminds me, I really need to get rid of that tree in my garden!)

title: Dremel 3D filament spool holder for 123-3D housebrand spools

description.text:
This is a filament reel or spool holder for non-Dremel reels or spools. This holder holds the 1kg spools with an outside diameter of 200mm, width of 64mm and a hole diameter of 52mm (as supplied for instance by the 123-3D Housebrand) and "05kg core" core for holding the 0.5kg spools with an inside diameter of 50mm and a width of 40mm. It fits exactly inside the Dremel 3D20 printer. I fit this one on the right side of the printer so that I can both fit the standard Dremel filament or the other spool size (I used a mirror image of the filament guide for that: see amongst my other things). I do find that these reels are varying quite a lot in dimensions and that some touch the y-axis-stepper motor just a tad: I had to remove some flash from the reel to make them run smoothly.

Fitting the holder requires opening the bottom cover and exchanging the two screws that are there with longer ones.

Fitting the reel on the holder works best with the plate in the bottom position.

author: aknaap

description.text:
With my new Filastruder and filawinder in hand I have quickly filled the couple of empty plastic spools I've been saving, I also wanted some smaller spools for 250G runs of filament for some custom colours.

I designed these to be simple to make with materials at hand that would fit the filawinder spooler and wont bind on the servo arm. It is close on the first position so you may need to move back one notch.

By using the same sides and varying the spool drum width (90mm postal tube) you can have 250G, 500G,1Kg spools, or even bigger if you like.

Measurements:

End diameter = 200mm
Centre hole Diameter = 40mm
Drum Diameter = 90mm

I designed around a 90mm postal tube cut into the following lengths:

25mm = 250G
50mm = 500G
90mm = 1Kg

I've done the calculations for PLA and ABS for 1.75mm filament not for 3mm

I strongly suggest to cut out the additional reinforcing pieces as well. These strengthen the spool hole considerably and should allow for multiple reuse on the filawinder.

NOTE: DO NOT put in oven or heated dehydrator to dry filament once on spool as hotglue will come unstuck. I totally forgot about the hotglue and found out the hard way doh! See photo above, it was easy to repair though and didn't have to re-spool phew!

Using the following calculators I calculated drum capacity based on my spool specs:

http://www.ingersollrandproducts.com/lifting/winches/drum.htm

From which the recommended working drum capacity (in meters) is used to calculate filament weight in either ABS/PLA

http://ideee.3deee.ch/?page_id=816

Some additional headroom has been allowed for as you'll see if you do the calculations yourself.

You can see by the photo of the spool on the scale how the capacity is (250g), this was taken after taring with an empty spool

1) Cutout x2 sides and highly recommend the x2 reinforcing pieces.

2) Cut length of 90mm postal tube to suite:
250g = 25mm
500g = 50mm
1Kg = 90mm

3) use a hot-glue gun to apply glue to one end of the postal tube and align with the centre marking on the first side.

4) Repeat for the second side, I found it easier to lie the 2nd side piece flat and apply glue to tube then look through centre to align as I apply pressure. You have a couple of seconds before the hot-glue sets to quickly align as best as you can. NOTE: I make sure the filament securing holes are opposite but is not that important.

5) optionally glue and align the two reinforcing piece, one to each side.

NOTE: the engrave line goes on the inside

Sides

I used a laser diode engraver (embazer) to cut the cardboard but can be easily handcut or use a proper laser cutter to save time and give you the accuracy. The centre line of the side pieces should be an engrave only cut as this is an alignment locator mark to aid gluing for assembly.

Emblazer settings for 3mm cardboard:
Engrave Cut Centre Line: 3500mm/min 100% 1 pass
Cut Through rest: 1000mm/min 100% 8 passes

Tube

I handcut the tube by first marking with a compass set to the correct width from one end. I used a hacksaw and slowly turned the cylinder as I made small cuts along the line.

This allowed me to get nice square ends without collapsing the cardboard tube.

If you have an easier way please share

Tools

Laser Cutter (easy) or knife/scissors (harder)
Hacksaw (fine tooth)
Compass to mark cut off
Hot Glue gun.

Material

3mm Cardboard
90mm Postal Tube

title: M3 bolt locknut with handle (15mm diameter)

description.text:
I needed a handle for a locknut M3 bolt to easily Z level one of my printers and I designed this quickly to do that job. Works fine for me. Outside diameter for the handle is ~15mm for my coarse fingers (works fine also with normal fingers). Insert a M3 nut into the hole, then screw in the M3 bolt, then insert the second M3 nut in the M3 bolt from the downside of the base and tighten it, there is no hole for the M3 nut in the downside to allow an easy tightening. Press/insert the top part (optional) to close the thingy and you are done. Tolerances taken into account, it should fit well. Use some glue if you want. Dimensions 15-16mm diameter x 15mm height for the normal one and 15-16mm x 9mm height for the slim version. Prints without support. After printing some of them I recommend usin PLA better than ABS cause this is a small thing and you need resolution, otherwise ABS prints will require some sanding. Not a heavy duty part, you know, it is just a thumbscrew. FreeCAD source included just in case you want to customize it. This is an enhancement for my other design here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1504679

Hint: You could Z-scale up it a bit, but remember that the M3 nut insert will also grow...
Hint2: You don't have to destroy the top cap to remove it, just unscrew the downside M3 nut 15mm, add a second m3 nut to make there a locknut, then unscrew the M3 bolt using the locknut, the cap will be pushed out by the screw's head.
Hint3: Don't force tightening the slim version, it is fragile.

Enjoy!

A trash can for your excess extruded filament.

Maybe it's just me but I'm constantly extruding filament that I then throw at the trash and it inevitably hooks on something on the way there and ends up creating a layer of plastic hair on the floor. Well no more!

It's not perfect yet but this little trash can does a surprisingly good job of catching and trapping filament that you drop into it's mouth. It also doubles as a holder for your tweezers.

I've sized it to fit on my Fabricator Mini (so 70mm diameter - 2.75 inches).

Prints in two separate parts. I didn't use a raft on the lid so as not to break the long thin sections.

I printed in PLA, but the lid might be better in abs so the little arms have more flexibility. Though for me the PLA has not broken (yet), I tried to make it thick enough to survive but thin enough to have some flex. I also suspect that the PLA does a better job of not grabbing the filament as you drop it in, where ABS or something flexible would have more grip and prevent the filament from going through the lid.

remixed_from.author: Parkinbot
remixed_from.title: Cut your own gears with profile shift - OpenSCAD library

description.text:
This is an example to make any gears by a gearcutting process. I've worked in the idea of parkinbot.
Crown gears are not a kind of bevel gears. Small gear of crown gears can be moved along it's axis, so there is no precision required. see wikipedia if you need more information.
Very often it is used as cheap gears in toys. Crown gear is made on punched thin sheetmetal. This shape cannot be copied to FDM printing.

Printed thing:
it is printed on the print?.stl files. I have made the holder as a quick and dirty design. Small gear is to small for printed plastic pins, I have used a 3mm steel rod (of a linear slider of an old CD drive). Maybe this gears can be used for educational. I don't see annother practical use.

stl files:
Most problem is the work style of openscad. It generates the cutting tool 100 times and seperately all its vertices to memory.
Then it makes a calculation process to find out the final shape of the object. This results in a very long rendering time because of nested for() loops. Most time I've got in my trials is >1 hour at a 100teeth gear. The mathematical system is very simple. Most work is needed to find out the computational limits and workarounds.

  • load crown.scad, uncomment gear1().
  • render [F6] and generate .stl files
  • uncomment crown_gear().
  • render [F6] and generate .stl files
  • load print.scad
  • select module you want to render and generate .stl files
    I have made this 2-step process because it would be hard to design the holder when the crown gear needs to be rendered every time. Also, I have found out, creating the crown gear needs a simple hull cylinder. Inserting spokes and hubs will need more computational power and patience of programmer. It's better to do this at a second process.
    (I'm happy to get this solution, even it was a hard process with repairs of non manifold stl's)
    I have tested to make high tooth count. This is not perfect for educational use. Characteristics of the crown gear system can be seen better at smaller tooth count.
    Also, I have tested to make hypoid and bevel gears in the crown cutting process. Hypoid gears normally require a twisted small gear, this will have a lot more vertices and data. So I have used a linear small gear, it will have more compromizes. Bevel crown gear needs some bugfixes. Because I'm working at annother idea to cut real bevel gears, I have not finished the work at bevel crown gears. (It would be a combination of a small spur gear and a crown gear in a matching angle <> 90deg). You will see the result if you'll change the parameters in scad file.
    A basic idea in my work on a gear library is the origin point [x,y,z]=[0,0,0]. Axis of the gears will match in the origin point of coordinate system. Position of the thick_end of gears is not needed to make teethcutting process. Gears can be moved easily by translate() and rotate() commands to every point you need.
    Annother idea: It is possible to make gears with irregular teeth if you change the tool gear (linear_extrude command) to import of your own gear stl file. Feel free to play with.

gears.scad is a copy of parkinbot's Gear cutting. I have made a change to smoothen the foot of teeth. This will reduce data by 5%.

description.text: Small printeable Inkle loom for weaving belts, bands, etc.  The loom attaches to most tabletops with the two C-clamps.  Alternatively there are slots in the clamp holders to thread a strap or velcro band so that you can strap the loom to your leg in order to use it anywhere...In a park, on the subway, etc.

With a jigsaw you could make this out of plywood and some dowels in about 15 minutes - but no, you are a Plastic Person and you are going to print it! You need seven tubes, two clamps (if you are using them) and one of everything else. I believe I used M3x10 bolts for the body, M4x45s to attach the tubes and tensioner and M5x50s for the clamps. The table clamps go through the slots provided and point away from the loom so that the business side of the loom will face you when it is clamped to a table. If you don't know how to warp and use an Inkle loom, there are lots of resources online. I've attached a Rhino screenshot to show the warping pattern. The C-clamp design is a derivation of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:30935 by Chewdonkey

We used a lock pin as the challenge to our puzzle as in order to complete the assembly you have to lock the pin into all the other parts creating a lock. The other challenge of our puzzle was to input the pieces in the correct orientation as there is a specific way to input the pieces.

The challenge we had designing this puzzle was making the puzzle easy to understand, but not too simple. We did his by making it clear where the pieces should fit into. description.text:
This is a Cassegrain antenna dish, due to the convex secondary reflector.  The optics have been calculated appropriately, such that if you somehow managed to smooth out the surfaces and make them shiny, this would focus a far away light into a small spot in the center of the dish (where the receiver would be).  
UPDATE: The files have been updated to make this easier to print.

Print the parts list.  Jam the two halves of the dish into the socket to hold them together.  There's an alignment hole in the secondary reflector so you can insert a short pieces of 3mm filament to hold that part together.  Realistically, you'll probably have to use some glue as well.  Finally, snap the socket onto the ball stand and point at your target of interest.
The scad file is parametric, and it'll automatically recalculate the optics if you choose different dimensions.  If your calibration has a thread width other than the default 0.42mm, you may want to adjust the t parameter in the OpenSCAD file to match, such that the dish will print out exactly two threads thick.

title: Printed front axle for Mercedes Unimog 1:16 model truck

description.text:
About two years ago I motorized a Bruder toys Mercedes Unimog in 1:16 scale and equipped it with (Atmel AVR-based) IR remote control. Because the Bruder chassis front axle did not have steering (fixed front axle), I constructed an steering front axle using aluminium profiles (see last photo).  
Now, with a reprap printer available I constructed the front axle again in openscad and printed it. It has an adjustable tie rod (vitamin, non printed) and is controlled by a micro servo at the front (see photos). The axle can steer and tilt. The construction principle is just a basic Achsschenkellenkung (German), I believe in English it is called Ackermann- or A-steering.  
I reused the vitamins from the old aluminium profile axle, particularly the ball couplings for the tie rod and the servo connector.  
Update 2013-09-20: The servo connector arm broke after a few days of operation. I have made the connector thicker and removed the inner connector bar and replaced it with a hull from the servo attachment point to the axle arm, thereby hopefully eliminating any notch stress. (see updated scad and stl files)

The scad code is commented and mostly parametric.  
The frontaxle_complete* files show all parts combined.  
The following parts need to be printed: _body, _armright, _armleft and _servoconnector. The arms need to be printed upside down, so the arms for the tie rod are at the print bed. The arms left and right are modelled with a support column which is cut off after printing. If you want to print with the support your slicer offers, you can disable the support in the scad file.  
The servo connector is attached to the underside of either the left or the right axle arm by both the M3 bolt used for steering the arm and an additional 3mm alignment hole. I have simply glued a short length of 3mm filemant through the servo connectors alignment hole into the the axle arms alignment hole for fixing the servo connector to the arm.  
The Vitamins should be obvious from the photos. All bolts and nuts are M3. The arms have both a nut trap on the inside, use a nyloc nut to fit the wheel axle there.
